Introduction

RestREco project (PI Prof.Jim Harris) : https://restreco.com/

The RestREco project studies ecosystems recovery after industrial or agricultural use. The main idea behind the project is that we will never be able to restore ecosystems to their prior state (because of the climate change, population increase, the technology developments etcf). So, we need to develop some new criteria to manage ecosystem restoration: for instance restore to some sufficiently complex and resilient state (so called restoration to complexity).

Soil microbiome is just one of the many aspects considered by the project. Soil samples were collected from tens of sites in Scotland and in England, which had been previously exposed to intensive Industrial (quarrying) or Agricultural use. The dataset selected for this analysis includes only woodland (additionally including a small number of ancient woodland sites and woodland re-wilding sites). The soil microbial community was assessed using 16S-amplicon sequencing.

Import of QIIME2 data to Phyloseq

The source data for this analysis was prepared in QIIME2. The QIIME2 data format is called QIIME2 artifacts, and has the QZA file extension. We will import QZA files to R using qza_to_phyloseq() function from qiime2R package. The Phyloseq object is the most popular R data format for metagenomics data. It provides a container for joint storage of feature/counts table, taxonomy, phylogeny and samples metadata (and some other types of data not used in this example).

# Required library
library(qiime2R) 

# During knitting setwd() may work for the current chunk only
setwd("C:\\Users\\alexe\\OneDrive - Cranfield University\\Work\\topics\\metagenomics\\maria_2024\\practical_final")

# Source files: assuming files in "data" sub-folder and 
# using "\\" for Windows path separator
feature_table_qza <- "data\\feature_table.qza"
rooted_tree_qza <- "data\\rooted_tree.qza"
taxonomy_qza <- "data\\taxonomy.qza"
metadata_tsv <- "data\\samples.txt"

# Read data
data.phy <- qza_to_phyloseq(
    features = feature_table_qza,
    tree = rooted_tree_qza,
    taxonomy = taxonomy_qza,
    metadata = metadata_tsv
    )

# Cleanup
rm(feature_table_qza, rooted_tree_qza, taxonomy_qza, metadata_tsv)
detach("package:qiime2R", unload=TRUE) # unload qiime2R package

Exclude low abundant taxa

Metagenomics data are very sparse even after agglomerating to class level.
To reduce sparsity, here we keep only classes with counts >10 in at least 10 samples.
These thresholds are arbitrary.
The thresholds for the final analysis may be different.

# x in filter_taxa() stands for the rows of the feature table 
# (rows = taxa, columns = samples)
BacIndAgriClassAbund.phy <- filter_taxa(BacIndAgriClass.phy,

Normalize by total count per sample

Phyloseq function transform_sample_counts() allows applying a function over samples. The function takes the x argument, which refers to a column within the feature table (remember: taxa= rows, samples=columns).

transform_sample_counts() may be used for normalization, such as scaling or centering per sample.

For simplicity, in this tutorial we will normalize by total count per sample. Then we scale the fractions by the median, and round to integers because some of the downstream functions expect integer counts, rather than fractions.

An alternative commonly used way of normalizing microbial data is rarefaction: equalizing depth in samples by random removal of data from the samples with higher depth. In R, the rarefaction curves could be plottred using vegan::rarecurve(), then the rarefaction may be applied using phyloseq::rarefy_even_depth().

Its important to remember that after combining samples or filtering taxa the normalization should be repeated.

# Counts per sample before normalization
plot(colSums(otu_table(BacIndAgriClassAbund.phy)), 
     ylab="Count", xlab="Samples", xaxt="n", 
     main="Counts per sample before normalization")

# Calculate median count per sample before normalization (33,183)
countsPerSample <- colSums(otu_table(BacIndAgriClassAbund.phy))
medianCount <- median(countsPerSample)

# Normalize by total count per sample
BacIndAgriClassAbundNorm.phy  = transform_sample_counts(BacIndAgriClassAbund.phy, 
  function(x) x / sum(x))

# Scale and round (to have integer counts instead of fractions)
BacIndAgriClassAbundNorm.phy  = transform_sample_counts(BacIndAgriClassAbundNorm.phy, 
  function(x) round(x*medianCount))

# Counts per sample after normalization
plot(colSums(otu_table(BacIndAgriClassAbundNorm.phy)), 
     ylab="Count", xlab="Samples", xaxt="n", 
     main="Counts per sample after normalization",
     ylim=c(min(countsPerSample),max(countsPerSample)))

# Clean-up
rm(BacIndAgriClassAbund.phy, countsPerSample, medianCount)

Alpha diversity

Alpha diversity describes the richness and/or evenness of microbial community within a single sample.

Plots

There are many measures of Alpha diversity. Here we plot Shannon and Simpson indices only.

plot_richness(BacIndAgriClassAbundNorm.phy, 
              measures=c("Shannon", "Simpson"),
              color="Region", x="Region", 
              title="Alpha diversity vs Region") +
  geom_boxplot()

              measures=c("Shannon", "Simpson"),
              color="Former_landuse", x="Former_landuse", 
              title="Alpha diversity vs Former Land Use") +
  geom_boxplot()

Estimating statistical significance

Here we will explore different statistical models to estimate what factors may affect the Shannon diversity.
Visual assessment of the plots suggests that alpha diversity may depend on the former land use and region.

In general, the statistical modelling should account for study design and for sparsity/compositionality of the data.

The design may include mixed model, nesting and croissing the factors.

Because of the compositionality (relative nature) and high sparsity of the standard statistical tests assuming normality of distributions usually are not appropriate for microbial data. Instead, it is recommended to use non-parametric tests (or specialized and permutation-based tests).

Mixed models

The highly significant non-parametric Wilcoxon test is sufficient for confirming that alpha diversity changes depending on the land use. The mixed models will not be used for the final analysis of alpha diversity.

However, mixed models may be better suited for RestREco design account for uncertainty between the replicas within each site:

https://www.modernstatisticswithr.com/regression.html#mixedmodels

Mixed models with lme4 could be applied to pH and conductivity analysis.

Later we may also apply mixed models to soil community composition. However, adonis2 does not accept the lme4 syntax. So, we will need to consider using restricted permutations and modifying the distances calculations instead of using the extended R formula syntax?

Compare mixed models using syntax as implemented in lme4 package

Beta diversity

Beta diversity is often illustrated by plots showing unconstrained ordination of samples.

Term ordination in ecology is used for dimentionality reduction and visualization techniques (similar to PCA). The idea is to make a 2D (or 3D) image that would reflect similarity/distances between samples (or taxa). The plot should show similar samples (or taxa) close to each other, while the dissimilar samples (or taxa) should be drown far apart.

Plotting

Calculating unconstrained ordination

Technically, an (unconstrained) ordination procedure includes two main steps:

  • calculating distances between samples, and
  • making a plot to reflect these distances in 2D image in a best possible way.

In the example below we use Bray-Curtis distance and PCoA method for making the plot. See help to the ordinate() function (?ordinate) to find information about other available distances and methods.

Here we consider the unconstrained ordination only. The constrained ordination includes additional steps, which allow adding some environmental gradients (e.g.soil pH) to the plot: so we can see how the samples & taxa are positioned along these gradients.

ord <- ordinate(BacIndAgriClassAbundNorm.phy, 
                distance = "bray",
                method = "PCoA")

Plotting with Phyloseq

Beta diversity, in effect, is an unconstrained ordination of samples. The samples located closely on the plot have similar microbial communities, the samples located far apart have very distinct microbial communities.

plot_ordination(BacIndAgriClassAbundNorm.phy, ord, type="samples",
                color="Former_landuse") + geom_point(size=3) +
  stat_ellipse() +
  ggtitle("Beta diversity", 
          subtitle="PCoA with Bray-Curtis distances")+ 
  theme_bw()

plot_ordination(BacIndAgriClassAbundNorm.phy, ord, type="samples",
                color="Region") + geom_point(size=3) +
  stat_ellipse() +
  ggtitle("Region", 
          subtitle="PCoA with Bray-Curtis distances")+ 
  theme_bw()

# Clean-up
rm(ord)

PERMANOVA with Vegan::Adonis2

Judging by the Beta diversity plots the soil communities are quite different depending on the region or prior use.

As it was noted earlier, the microbial data requires specialized tests. The most commonly used test for estimating Beta diversity statistical significance is PERMANOVA (PERmutation based Multivariate ANOVA) implemented in adonis2() function from the vegan package.

In the example below you may note this formula within the vegan::adonis2() function:
~Region/Use/Site.
This is a way of describing multi-layer nested designs in R.

Also, you may note the strata=Region term: it does not allow permutations between regions.

The modelling shows that the microbial communities are very different
- between the studied regions, and
- between the land use types within each region, and
- between the sites for each land use within each region.

However, this formula considers all the factors as fixed, and does not account for the mixed effect design. Unfortunately, adonis2 does not understand the lme4 syntax. So, we will have to find a way of how to achieve mixed effects effect using restricted permutations and distance calculations. Googling mixed models adonis2 finds a number of discussions about it. Some references about restricted permutations and nested designs are given later.

library(vegan)

# This lmer mixed model syntax fails in adonis2: 
# adonis2(bray.dist ~ Region/Use + (1|Site),
#         data = data.df, permutations=1000)

# Using fixed effects nested model
adonis2(bray.dist ~ Region/Use/Site,
        strata = data.df$Region,
        data = data.df, permutations=1000)
## Permutation test for adonis under reduced model

This result of PERMANOVA test shows that all three studied factors have significant effect on the microbial community: the Region, the Prior Land Use, and the Sites within each Region/ Land Use group. The R2 column shows the relative contributions of each factor into the total variance of the microbial communities.

Breifly:
If factor B is nested within factor A (e.g.we have multiple sites within each type of the land use), then the typical ANOVA (or regression) R formula could be written in the follwoing way:
A + B %in% A This means that we are interested in effect of factor A abd factor B nested within A.
An equivalent way of writing this formula is
A + A:B
For R experts, it highlights that, in fact, we a looking for effects of A and interaction of A with B.
The syntax A/B (used in our code) is a shortcut for A + B %in% A

Visualising taxonoimy

Visualizing taxonomy is an important part of exploring microbial data.

Phyloseq provides plot_bar() function that outputs a ggplot object that can be directly piped to the geom_bar() layer. ## Combining low-abundant taxa

Combining low-abundant taxa may make the taxa bar-plot clearer.

Unfortunately, plot_bar() does not provide such option. The code below illustrates how it can be done (modified from the Phyloseq author post https://github.com/joey711/phyloseq/issues/494 ).

It includes 3 steps:

  • Converting Phyloseq object to a large data frame using psmelt() function
  • Substituting rare phyla to others (e.g.Phyla with count <1%)
  • Using the updated data frame for the ggplot stacked barplot

Combining samples

Phyloseq function merge_samples() allows to combine samples, so we can compare groups of samples. In this example we will combine soil samples by the Prior Land Use.

Important: after merging samples, the data should be re-normalised!

# Merge samples in groups (warnings are OK) 
landUse.phy <- merge_samples(BacIndAgriClassAbundNorm.phy, "Former_landuse")
landUse.phy

## phy_tree()    Phylogenetic Tree: [ 79 tips and 78 internal nodes ]
# Re-Normalize after merging samples !
landUse.phy  = transform_sample_counts(landUse.phy, function(x) x / sum(x))

# Convert Phyloseq object to large data frame
MeltData.df <- psmelt(landUse.phy)

Differential abundance with ancombc2

ANCOMBC package implements a method for differential abundance analysis, which takes into account the compositionality of microbial data: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-020-17041-7

Like Vegan and Phyloseq, ANCOMBC is a very popular package, and it can directly accept the Phyloseq objects.

detach("package:phyloseq", unload=TRUE) # unload phyloseq package (to avoid warnings from ANCOMBC)

# Lad package
library(ANCOMBC)

# Estimate differential abundances
# ~5min, multiple warnings are OK
ancom.output = ancombc2(data = BacIndAgriClassAbundNorm.phy, tax_level = "Class",
                fix_formula = "Former_landuse", 
                group = "Former_landuse", 
                p_adj_method = "holm", alpha = 0.05, pairwise = TRUE,
                prv_cut = 0.10, lib_cut = 1000, 
                n_cl = 4, verbose = TRUE)

# Clean-up
detach("package:ANCOMBC", unload=TRUE) # unload ANCOMBC package (just in case)

Extract results from ancombc2 output

The ancombc2 output contains many components that we dont need for the downstream analysis. We only need the table with results. Moreover, within this table we will only use selected columns describing Former Landuse (ignoring the data about intercept).

The columns that we need are:

  • taxon: the taxa (at Class level in our case)
  • lfc_Former_landuseIndustrial: Log Fold Change (Industrial vs Agriculture)
  • se_Former_landuseIndustrial: Standard error for LFC
  • W_Former_landuseIndustrial: The statistics calculated by ANCOMBC
  • p_Former_landuseIndustrial: p-value for the statistics (w/o the multiple testing correction)
  • q_Former_landuseIndustrial: significance after the multiple testing correction
  • diff_Former_landuseIndustrial: Is this taxon differentially abundant ? (TRUE/FALSE)
  • passed_ss_Former_landuseIndustrial: Has the taxon passed the additional ANCOMBC check? (TRUE/FALSE)
# Extract the results table

  factor(dif_results.df$direct, levels = c("Positive LFC", "Negative LFC"))
dif_results.df$taxon = 
  factor(dif_results.df$taxon, levels = dif_results.df$taxon)
  
# Make plot
dif_results.df %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = taxon, y = lfc_Former_landuseIndustrial, fill = direct)) + 
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.7, color = "black", 
             position = position_dodge(width = 0.4)) +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = lfc_Former_landuseIndustrial - se_Former_landuseIndustrial, 
                      ymax = lfc_Former_landuseIndustrial + se_Former_landuseIndustrial), 
                  width = 0.2, position = position_dodge(0.05), 
                  color = "black") + 
    labs(x = "Class", y = "Log fold change") +  
    ggtitle(label = "Differentially abundant taxa", 
            subtitle="Prior land use: Industrial vs Agricultural") +
    scale_fill_discrete(name = NULL) +
    scale_color_discrete(name = NULL) +
    theme_bw() + 
    theme(panel.grid.minor.y = element_blank(),
          axis.text.x = element_text(size = 6, angle = 60, hjust = 1))

A number of microbial classes showed significantly different abundance between Post-Industrial and Post-Agricultural soil samples. This result confirms the previous Beta diversity findings suggesting that the prior lend use has a strong effect on soil microbial community in RestREco dataset.
